segments.text: what I call a legacy from President Walton.
We came here that he came as president.
He became president the same year that we came in as new members of the Department of History.
And I don't know when it started, but I know it was in full swing in the early 30s because I remember the people who were honored

this Christmas dinner or pre-Christmas dinner that he, presumably in the name of the college, but we always thought of it as coming from him, a Christmas dinner, which was given at the college a little bit before the Christmas holiday started, the Christmas vacation started, so that we could all get to it.
And this was a very beautiful family style dinner.
The platters were passed along, and it was for the faculty, and the teaching faculty, and the Experiment Station Extension Service people.
And I remember once we had one of the waiters at Old Speeds Hall, what we now would say a black or a Negro man.
And he was, we used to say colored in those days,
And he was honored with 25 years.
So you see, it was inclusive and democratic and rather nice.
And we used to enjoy those get-togethers so much, because we all knew each other.
How many people did you have at these get-togethers?
Oh, let me see.
I couldn't tell you.
Do you have any idea of them?
There might have been a couple of hundred on the faculty at that time, but I don't know how many in experimentation.
I'd say 150 at a conservative exercise.
Was there?
I'd say 150 at a conservative exercise.
Well, a faculty, but I don't know how many of experimentation and extension service people.
But you see, it was what we now would call a small group.
In those days, we called it a large group.
But we had a lovely time.
And afterwards, there would be some short speeches, mostly light in nature.
And then after the dinner, or toward the end of the dinner, we would sing Christmas carols together.
And I remember, particularly on one occasion, that Mr. Joe directed our singing.
And he was, by the way, the first director of the Cadet Singers before they had a professional director.
And Joe Wilk was very fond of music.
And they, of course, are still here.
And let me see.
Everybody had a wonderful time.
And we looked forward.
We practically expected them to do it to us.
And then, in the same vein,
And I call that a sort of legacy from President Walton.
How long did this go on?
How many years?
Oh, I remember definitely that it was going on in 35, but it went on much longer than that.
It went on to, oh, let me see, when somebody came in.
When did the Nancys come here?
I remember them and that.
And I remember the cigars in that.
So that was, it must have gone on up until, probably until President Walton retired.
I believe that it went on that whole long, long, long period so that I can differentiate between one of the meetings and another one of the meetings, or one of the dinners.
Later, we were served banquet style by plate.
And that was when it got larger, I think.
You see, it would be simpler to serve it like that.
And the cadet waiters used to serve us.
And we always had a thank you for the director of subsistence, whoever it was, a formal thank you, and for the cadets who served us.
Duncan was director of subsistence.
What's that?
Duncan was director of subsistence.
At that time.
was director of subsystem.
And Spiesa had just, I think, gone off.
Spiesa Hall is named for him.
And, of course, Duncan Hall is named for Mr. Duncan.
How was the food?
Oh, wonderful.
Really?
Oh, delicious food.
Oh, they didn't skimp us.
They didn't skimp us.
Incidentally, along that very line, there was a dining or a meal, no matter what it sounds,
At Speza Hall.
Yes, that's where we had it.
And one of the prominent items on the menu was fresh, roasted and thin air corn on the cob.
Oh, that was at summertime.
Yeah.
And somebody was congratulating Duncan about it.
And he said, yeah, that's all right.
The boys are having the same thing today.
I was down in Houston looking the markets over, and there was quite a bunch of fresh corn on the market.
And I got 32 bushels sealed up here.
So the bars were not always shorted, you see.
I haven't heard too many complaints about the food from that period at all.
Most of the people I talked to would still thought the food was very good.
Maybe the young men were better trained and better behaved, perhaps, in that period.
But anyway, that's when they were still doing hazing.
And that has sort of simmered off, I think.
In the same connection, there was another gathering of faculty, and I say faculty, Experiment Station, and Extension Service.
We were just one group together when the New Year's reception
that President and Mrs. Walton gave.
I think that is still being continued, but I'm not sure.
They may be dividing it, too, because the groups are so much larger.
It may not be one long affair.
But that New Year's reception, well, we wouldn't have missed it for anything.
Mrs. Walton had the most heavenly food you can imagine.
And it was so informal.
It was so, we all knew each other.
And I remember that on one occasion, one of the deans took his napkin and picked up a few elegant tidbits that Mrs. Walton always had and folded up.
He was taking this to his children, so they'd enjoy that part.
What name was this?
What's that?
Who was this that did this?
Who was the dean that did it?
Oh, should I say that?
Certainly.
Well, it was Dean Winkler.
Oh, my.
Well, Dean Winkler was then dean of what was it?
Education.
Education, I think.
And we knew them well, too.
He died some years ago.
But Mrs. Winkler is still living here.
I really shouldn't give names because that was so natural.
And so you might have done it with family.
But that was always President Walton's motto.
We are one family.
You see, it was a beautiful idea to reiterate.
And also that one cooperation.
He used those two phrases a good bit.
And then they have colored the whole thing.
The whole attitude had something to do with it.
Only to stress the wrong syllable, cooperation.
Yes, we all do say cooperation.
And I think we all got to saying and probably having fun.
And then if one copies somebody else, one gets the same habit oneself.
It's very interesting.
Let me see.
There was something I wanted to say there about that.
But I believe that's all, Mrs. Walton.
Mrs. Walton served elegant meals.
We've been there to dinner.
Oh, wonderful.
And Ethel Burgess is the daughter still living here.
And little Mrs. M.L.
Cashin, Mason Lee Cashin's wife, is Dr. Walton's granddaughter.
He had two sons here who are doctors, I think.
Dr. Turner Walton has retired, helped on .
And Lee.
Yes, and Lee.
But he has a son who is also practicing now.
So you see they've gone into medical and stayed here, the two sons and their sons.
And let me see, another social event was
Mrs. Duncan's Halloween party.
And honestly, when anybody started something like that, all the rest of us expected it to go on forever.
It was such a nice, steady feeling we had.
But she gave Halloween parties on Halloween night.
Now, I think that did not last so long.
The Duncans were already elderly when we came.
So I think that was a short duration.
But I remember one.
Of course, it was her party.
It was the Duncans gave the party.
It was not a college affair.

But I think some, one of the military men in the military department, they had a very handsome and charming secretary, not so young as I remember her, but not in the 20s, beyond the 20s, and maybe beyond 30s.
And one of the military people
called Mrs. Duncan to order because she didn't invite the secretary.
So you see how things were.
I don't know whether she really did it or not, but she was not obliged to because it was a private party.
Then I don't know whether I told you how we used to shop.
I heard, this is secondhand, I heard from
the daughter of a long ago head of the history department, Professor Fountain, whose memorial bronze tablet is in the YMCA chapel, I believe they call it now.
And she said, she was the one that had the history far, far back.
And I have heard her talk.
So some of these things.
are secondhand from her and from Mrs. Camel.
Mrs. Camel and Mrs. Cofer.
They were long-time, but not as long time as Mrs. Marsteller, who was the fountain, and married Marsteller, who succeeded Dean Francis as head of the veterinary school.
She said that when they lived here, when she was young here,
They had to get to Bryan with almost a day's journey, because they had to go by buggy to get their shopping.
But there was a grocery, and at Northgate, a few, well, there was a grocery established the year we came.
You remember Luke's, Luke and Charlie.
Very well known.
So much so that everybody went to Luke and Charlie.
Luke was a prince.
He was a prince.
Do you remember their full names?
Luke.
Patronel.
Patronel.
Patronel.
Patronella or Patronello, I don't know.
His widow, Elsie, a very fine woman.
She had 20 years of widowhood and then married a retired colonel here who was a fine person.
She's had two wonderful husbands.
And she acted with dignity and poise through those 20 years, I told her that month.
And she lives here.
Now, Luke's.
But he was the grocer here.
But at his funeral, I have never seen so sick at heart and so much weeping as was seen there.
I never have.
We all loved Luke.
And he had a- Who was Charlie?
Charlie?
Charlie Oversteady.
was in business with him in the grocery business in Northgate.
Then when the development started across Texas Avenue, when Texas Avenue became a road, a street, Luke moved over there in a new neighborhood and continued his business there in his own name, Luke's.
But Luke and Charlie was such a familiar name in the older days.
before there was any Texas Avenue, that one child was reported to have said her evening prayer, something about Matthew, Mark, Luke, and John, saying, Matthew, Mark, Luke, and Charlie.
So you see, he was one of us, too, but not, of course, of the staff.
And later, of course, after this buggy period, which we didn't know anything about, there were a lot of new high cars.
You know, they all had so much at the top, especially the Fords, I think.
And we came down with the A, what was ours?
Max.
Maxwell.
And then we would go to town by car.
What road did you take to town?
Oh, College Road.
That's all there was.
We didn't have anything else.
What was the condition of the road?
Could you describe it?
Well, it was like any old road would be.
Nothing gray on.
It was not paved or was paved?
Pretty primitive, I would say.
No, it was not paved.
It was not paved.
Oh, it was not paved, no.
Not even gravel.
Yeah, gravel.
But it was passable.
We never had any trouble going in there.
And how long did it take you?
Can you remember how long it took you to get, say, from your house to downtown Bryan, to the shopping district?
I don't know.
12, 15 minutes.
Oh, now we can get anywhere in 10, 15 minutes.
Now, certainly.
But I was wondering when.
No, it must have been half an hour or so to get down there, I imagine.
And we had just this little one grocery on the campus.
And of course, it was not stocked as well as the several ANPs and so on in town.
Of course, just, we, I think it was here, or they started shortly after we came, the interurban, which ran from, did it start from old Aggieland Inn, or more to Northgate?
More from the gate, I think.
More, it was more Northgate, what we now call Northgate.
There was an interurban that rode into town, and where it stopped in town, or where the station wasn't down, I can't remember, because we didn't use it except in emergency.
And it came right through Cabot Street, which is now Cabot Street.
In fact, some people living over there near Cabot here in North Oakwood used the end of that paving ramp on tracks as their driveway.
You can see.
I can see that it is the remains of the old road.
Then, of course, they changed to buses.
And that's modern.
So you don't want to know about anything modern.
How often did the interurban run?
How often?
How often was the schedule of the interurban?
How often did a car come and go?
I can't remember.
Near as I can remember, about every quarter hour.
Quarter hour?
Was it that often?
How was it powered?
Was it electric or diesel or?
Overhead.
I think it was an overhead trolley.
It was a streetcar.
But we've always called it a streetcar.
And I don't know how many are left.
But there's some still left in.
Oh, there are buses up there in New York.
San Francisco still has a lot, I think.
42nd Street.
Leading to that, from that, or rather from the, I should say, that
a continuation of the family relationship of the employees, faculty, and so forth, at the college.
There is now a A&M retirees club, which means if you're retired, you're eligible.
And of course, not all go.
But we have a president, we have a secretary, and who reads the minutes, and we have a treasurer.
We have no constitution, no bylaws, no anything to break.
Very informal.
We can't break any constitution or bylaws or anything.
We just meet.
Do you know when this first started?
Oh, that may have been as long as 10 years ago.
But it's not an old thing.
Carnegie came in 56.
No, it may have been started in 60.
Maybe in there somewhere.
Because I remember who was working it up.
That was Mr. Carnegie, who came here.
He was in the insurance business.
And then he came in here and taught a few years.
And that made him a retired professor.
Where did he teach?
What department?
That's right.
What department did he teach in?
I think in business administration.
But I'm not quite sure, because we're just a few years, and we've had a number of people come in like that, retiring.
I'll tell you.
Oh, I could mention their names, but it's so recent.
We had a number that would come in, especially in the Army, would come in and teach some years and then be retired.
here, you see.
And they usually stayed here, like we do.
That's a nice place.
See, we can't get away from this place.
That's a nice place.
And we, for years, thought we'd retire up to Virginia to raise various properties up there.
But we can't get away from this place.
That's all there's to it.
And let me see.
So that retirees club, we meet about four or five times a year.
I think it's supposed to be four times.
have no constitution or bylaws or anything.
So we just do what we want to.
And we meet and pay for our dinners.
We've gone to Haldi Inn.
We've gone to Wyatt's.
We've gone to the Ramada.
We've gone out to the college memorial center.
We get a notion we want change.
Well, then we change.
And there's nothing that says we can't.
We just vote.
And we are about, the attendance is about 110.
So it kind of, that I think, or thereabouts.
And that crowds us pretty much in some places.
So we've had to make moves there.
But that's lots of fun.
We all love each other.
Because we're all so old.
Well, you get a chance to see a lot of people, I guess, at this that you don't get to see very often.
We're sort of mellowed, you might say.
So we all love each other.
There was an old entertainment.
There was Guyon Hall.
Do you know anything about Guyon Hall?
It was here when I was here.
But there was a fault in the construction there.
So I think that it hasn't lasted.
We lived right at the back of that Guyon Hall.
And what is now a parking lot, or I think it still is.
They make so many changes out there, you can tell.
It's a parking lot.
a parking lot by the Raleigh White.
Yes, and directly behind the new Rutter Center that they built over where G. Raleigh was.
Well, don't tell me about that.
I don't want to get lost again.
Well, right where G. Raleigh, right where
Guy in Hall was, they built this new complex.
Oh, they did.
The tower, I think, where they have a restaurant on top.
I never could understand why you had to go all the way up on the top of something to a restaurant.
But we did it in the Europa Hotel in Copenhagen, remember?
I think I did.
Rosebuds strewn all over the table for us.
We asked for a table for several.
This is extraneous.
This is a point.
little boy of five or six said when we took him to the circus, he said, why do they have to swing way up there?
Why can't they swing down here?
So we have a practical point of view here.
There was the cat a corner, approximately cat a corner, from the present YMCA building.
Only in those days, it didn't have the solariums on it.
It was just a narrower building.
And all our meetings, our women's clubs, and study clubs, and garden clubs, and things like that, always met there.
We didn't have the facilities that now exist with the Memorial Center then.
And later, we did meet at the Memorial Center.
Our women's organization, faculty-wise,
the study clubs, and the social club.
We had the social club.
I believe I told you about the social club.
It was organized mainly to look after the cadets, the boys who stayed, who couldn't get home for Christmas.
But we all went to it and took our children, and it was a very family time.
Do you have any idea how old the women's social club is?
When it began, maybe?
It was in existence when we came.
That's about as much as I can tell.
And the campus club was in existence.
I remember being invited to it.
What's the campus club?
The campus study club.
Oh, the campus club.
Yeah, I remember being invited to it the first year we were here.
And it still exists.
And I think they have a historian.
I think the historian is Mrs. Marie Ashton.
Marie Ashton, Mrs. Ashton.
And she might be able to tell you more of that if you wanted it.
But as I said, we used to meet at the Y.
And then, again, about these old buildings, almost cat a corner from the Y.
As it now stands, it's one of the old buildings.
And it was here when we came.
It was an old sort of barn-like structure that I think they called it Assembly Hall, but I'm not quite sure.
because there would be some assemblies there when we became uncertain about Guyon Hall.
And by the way, in Guyon Hall, there were no churches as such.
There were the Presbyterian group, the Methodist group, the Baptist group.
Have you heard about that?
No, I haven't.
Well, you see, it was small.
And there was not enough people to make a charter group and do it.
But after a while, we became established as churches.
Was it too far to go to Bryan, then?
In other words, you could have gone to church at Bryan.
No, but most of us didn't.
College stayed pretty much to itself.
Local patriotism.
Yes, I think it was a sense of chauvinistic patriotism, I think.
But in the basement of Gone Hall, I don't know why they dared let us be there, but I think it was the upper structure that was dangerous.
In the basement, there was a Union Sunday School.
And I think Mrs. Campbell and Mrs. Marsteller started that, and it was in existence when we came.
And I taught there five years for a group of boys who are now middle-aged men.
And the sons, and it was the sons, the boys class I had.
And we met there and sang there and had the only Sunday school.
Then they had somebody established a little later.
That was Mrs. Carper.
And I think Mrs. Carper and I can't remember who else.
established a youth meeting, a youth vespers, which I was asked to take part in.
I could tell you some amusing incidents there, but they're largely about the children.
But Catacorner, again, I'll get back with that old sort of barn-like structure where movies were shown.
I can't remember whether Wednesdays and Saturdays.
I can't remember.
I think so, but I can't remember.
Because Wednesday was an off night for the students.
I don't know if it is now.
Yeah, it is for military.
It's not for the students anymore, I think.
This is the old church night, Wednesday night.
Wednesday night was an off night for the...
I think they showed the movies then.
I know our elder son...

went to it and I believe Sam Ray later and we've gone to the movies there then and that's right I think where it's to the to the east is it east gate that comes over here to University what's now University Drive what was it then Old Sulphur Springs Road or something like that and
Yes, I've got a note to that.
Then I believe that the name of the dormitory now standing near there is Pereer Hall, but I can't remember all those names now.
But that was after old sweet Dean Pereer.
And if you asked me his first name, I could not tell you.
Could you?
He was from Virginia, so he was... His name was Charles, but I cannot be certain.
No, Pereira.
But he was a sweet elderly to old gentleman when we came.
And he lived over there on Quality Row and was a bachelor, was he not?
Yeah.
And he died not long after we came.
But while our children were small...
And we lived in that corner house.
And Bolton lived next to us by one house, Dean and Mrs. Bolton.
Bolton later became president on what they called Quality Row.
That was named long before we ever came.
He used to come down, used to live on Quality Row, and turn the corner and come down on our side street.
And as he passed,
the homes where there were young boys not going to school, and maybe girls too, young girls, before preschool age.
He'd come along, and they'd all come rushing over to him to be weighed.
So he would hold his cane up for them.
They would grab hold of the cane, and he would lift it, and he would tell them their weight.
So you see how family-like the whole thing was.
Dean Pereira, I just know him as a fine and scholarly gentleman.
Was he once head of the math?
I think so, yeah.
I think he was.
Then there's, let me see, is there anything else I can tell about that?
Except to emphasize the family-like character of the whole
small campus, because we didn't have any huge buildings.
We didn't even want them, I think.
And the campus now seems strange to many of us.
I've heard several say, oh, I'll never go near it.
But we went to the campus once by mistake, and we got lost.
And then we found where we once had lived, but there's so many one-way streets.
that we got off on other streets before.
But we managed to get home.
And you see, we now are.
So what else is there?
Can you think of any questions you'd like to ask?
No, I might like to have you describe your experiences with Dr. Mark Francis, possibly.
Oh, Dr. Mark Francis.
He lived on our side street just a half a block down.
And I knew Mrs. Francis very well.
In fact, she had gone with me several times to Houston.
Later, we went to Houston to shop.
Now, that would be in the late 40s, somewhere in the late 40s.
I mean, not our ages, but the late 40s chronologically.
And she was half shy and half full of fun.
a person, quite a person herself, but not the personality that her husband Mark Francis was.
In fact, there are many stories about him going about, some of which we heard.
He died while we still lived on the campus.
So that was in the 30s, you see, somewhere in there.
But he was retired, lived as a retired man, and it hurt him very much to be retired.
I remember that.
He was fussing a good bit about being retired.
And then his next in line, Dr. Marsteller, stepped up to be head of the veterinary school, dean of the veterinary school.
Dean Francis, I know we went over calling very promptly that Sunday morning when we heard that he had died and saw Mrs. Francis.
She was willing to see us.
But one of the stories that I remember told all around was that he would make a regular tour of the campus
and pick up all the discarded bottles.
What the bottles had been used for before, I leave to your imagination.
Because I think it was in Prohibition times.
But there were still bottles lying around.
And they were a disgrace to his soul, I think.
So he picked them up.
And when he died, they found the servant house just full.
of bottles.
I don't know what they did with them.
He didn't know what to do with them, so he parked them in his certain house.
In his certain house.
But it was told with great delight about him and pleasure, you see.
It was just nice of him.
He was kind of matter of fact.
And I do know some stories, which I'm not sure should go on tape, very mild ones.
Ray may know some others that definitely should not go on tape or be deleted.
I can't think of any right now that I dare say they were something.
Well, do you want me to tell you that one about the chief?
Well, he said, now the girls used to pout.
That's when the skirts became shorter and shorter.
And he said, and that must have been in his last years somewhere in...

30s maybe early 30s I can't remember when he died um the year I mean uh and he said that the girls now are are rouging their cheeks now with the skirts getting shorter all the time they'll have to rouge their other cheeks so that's that's the only one that I know about him except that he was um
He was always, always a character.
And I said, oh, yes, let me tell you this one.
He was off on a trip once by train.
We had trains in those days.
And he was off on a train trip, and Mrs. Francis expected him home on the night train.
I think it came around 12 o'clock at night and was in bed.
And but she left the door unlocked.
And we always left our doors unlocked.
We just could go to Brian and not think of locking up our house.
But how different it is now.
And she had left the door unlocked.
And someone, she heard a bang, bang, banging.
And I'm not quite sure we had doorbells, did we?
I can't remember.
Those were campus houses we lived in.
I can tell you a little bit about that if you'd like to know.

and somebody banged and she said come in I have the door unlocked come in and the banging kept on and she said come in you old fool and he still banged away so she went to the door and found it was a stranger had seen a light and wanted his way and then of course a little bit later a few moments later Dr. Francis himself came
And they were very sort of matter of fact.
And I remember one time after I brought her back from a Houston trip.
That must have been way back then, the 32.
I call that way back.
And no, wait a minute.
No, it was later than that.
But anyway, I brought her back from Houston.
And they all thought I was a pretty good driver.
So some of the women going to Houston, that was in the late
late 30s, before we built.

And many of us had to go down to get the hardware and things like that, to select hardware and things like that for the homes that we were building when the campus was cleared of faculty homes, except the president, and maybe some others.
I don't know.

I remember that some one of the ladies asked me would I please take over she didn't mind driving a road but would I please take over when we got into Houston itself because she didn't like to drive in traffic which didn't bother me and uh they and we're about the same age by the way and uh as I said I was taking Mrs. Francis home uh and some others from the
from the campus, whom I've invited to go along for shopping.
And Bryan didn't have all the stores that it now has, even back there 30 years ago.
And so when we drove up to approaching her house, here was Dr. Francis, the undemonstrative Dr. Francis, walking back and forth on the pavement.
We did have a few pavements, didn't we?
But usually there weren't any pavements or walks.
We just traipsed over everything.
And he was walking back and forth and back and forth.
And I told Mrs. Francis, I said, see, you see, he is worried to death about your coming home so late.
And of course, it wasn't very late because we wouldn't drive that late.
And she was more like a young girl being courted.
And she accepted that.
that interpretation of his walking back and forth.
The houses.
The houses that we had were campus houses.
When we came to ours, I think it was 12 years old.
But they were very flimsily constructed.
So the windows and the doors didn't fit very tightly.
So it wouldn't have been done in these days of energy and fuel
shortages because we had winter winds when we didn't want them and summer heat when we didn't want it.
And of course, there was no, we didn't have air conditioning and things like that.
But we did have, and we had wood stoves, wood and coal stoves when we first came.
And then gas was put in when?
A few years after we came.
In the 30s, I think.
It was in the late 20s because Thompson came to see us and we had just gotten there.
And I think that must have been before we went to visit him.
So it must have been in the late 20s.
I bet you were glad to get that gas stove.
That's what?
I bet you were glad to get that gas stove.
Oh, it was wonderful.
We had a friend visiting us at that time, and he was just as happy as we were.
An old family friend of ours who was more like an uncle to us girls.
But the houses were very flimsy.
Ours was painted green, and everybody else's was white.
So we felt...
We live in the greenhouse, not the white house.
And I can tell you one incident about it.
Our young son, who's now in the State Department, when he was, oh, I suppose, four, five, something like that, he was just a year old when we came here.
And he was in Sunday school, and he must have been judging by the...
The lesson, as it was given, he must have been about four or five, enough to understand that one must be grateful and thankful for God's good gifts.
And the teacher, I can tell you her name, told them, now what must we be thankful for?
